Our cuda implementation for LSTM uses cudnn libray, it has some limitation: the sequences in the mini-batch need to be sorted in descending order according to length. refers to 
https://docs.nvidia.com/deeplearning/sdk/cudnn-developer-guide/index.html#cudnnRNNForwardInferenceEx

issue.title: Inference on a batch of sequences of variable lengths has stopped working

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
I have a very simple model that takes a tensor containing a padded list of sequences of variable length with shape (minibatch_size, 1, max_num_rows, 24) plus a vector of lengths with shape (minibatch_size), and returns a tensor of predictions with shape  (minibatch_size, max_num_rows, 39). 

The model was trained with Pytorch, and later exported to ONNX using the Pytorch ONNX exporter. It worked fine with the ORT shared library compiled from source a month ago. However, I recompiled the library from code pulled from the ORT repository 3 days ago (Commit ID: 2714576d0ae89f553874394d12c1f3cb4724a6de) and it has stopped working. Somehow it appears that ORT is not able to infer the correct input shape from the supplied input tensor, and it is now using the dummy values from the ONNX export.

```
OrtRun failed . Error description: e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\providers\cpu\tensor\reshape_helper.h:38 onnxruntime::ReshapeHelper::ReshapeHelper (input_shape.Size() % size) == 0 was false. The input tensor cannot be reshaped to the requested shape. Input shape:{16,14,6,24}, requested shape:{-1,5,144}
Stacktrace:
e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\providers\cpu\tensor\reshape.h(34): onnxruntime::Reshape::Compute
e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\framework\sequential_executor.cc(119): onnxruntime::SequentialExecutor::Execute
e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\framework\utils.cc(514): onnxruntime::utils::ExecuteGraph
e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\session\inference_session.cc(707): onnxruntime::InferenceSession::Run
e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\session\onnxruntime_c_api.cc(461): OrtRun
0x140428993 (Unknown symbol)
0x1403ac779 (Unknown symbol)
0x1403b5a1e (Unknown symbol)
0x1403e9821 (Unknown symbol)
0x140506444 (Unknown symbol)
0x1405062ee (Unknown symbol)
0x1405061ae (Unknown symbol)
0x1405064d9 (Unknown symbol)
???: BaseThreadInitThunk
???: RtlUserThreadStart
```

The code I use to initialize the model is

```
  # Model constructor
    def __init__(self, numCols, numClasses, enableSoftmax = False):
        
        # Call the base constructor
        super().__init__()
        
        # Input image dimensions
        self.cnn_downscale_factor = 4
        self.num_cols = numCols
        self.num_classes = numClasses
        self.softmax_enabled = enableSoftmax
        
        # Initialize convolutional blocks.
        self.conv1 = nn.Conv2d( in_channels=1, out_channels=12, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1 )
        self.conv2 = nn.Conv2d( in_channels=self.conv1.out_channels, out_channels=24, kernel_size=3, stride=2, padding=1 )
        
        # Initialize RNN
        rnn_dim = 128
        dense_dim = 96       
        
        self.rnn_input_size = self.conv2.out_channels * self.num_cols // self.cnn_downscale_factor
        #self.rnn = nn.GRU( input_size=self.rnn_input_size, hidden_size=rnn_dim//2, num_layers=1, batch_first=True, bidirectional=True )
        self.rnn = nn.LSTM( input_size=self.rnn_input_size, hidden_size=rnn_dim//2, num_layers=1, batch_first=True, bidirectional=True )
        
        # Initialize dense stages
        self.dense1 = nn.Linear( rnn_dim, dense_dim )
        self.dense2 = nn.Linear( dense_dim, self.num_classes * self.cnn_downscale_factor )
```
An this is the code of the forward pass:

```
# Forward pass
    def forward(self, x, lengths):
        
        # Convolutional stage
        h = self.conv1( x )
        h = my_conv_activation( h )
        h = self.conv2( h )
        h = my_conv_activation( h )
        h = h.permute(0,2,3,1)
        h = h.reshape( -1, h.shape[1], self.rnn_input_size )
        
        # RNN stage
       
        # pack_padded_sequence so that padded items in the sequence won't be shown to the LSTM
        # the lengths tensor must be already divided by the granularity of the CNN stage (4)
        h = torch.nn.utils.rnn.pack_padded_sequence( h, lengths, batch_first=True, enforce_sorted=True )
        
        # run through RNN
        h, _ = self.rnn( h ) 
        
        # undo the packing operation
        h, _ = torch.nn.utils.rnn.pad_packed_sequence( h, batch_first=True )
        
        # Dense stages
        h = self.dense1( h )
        h = my_dense_activation( h )
        
        h = self.dense2( h )
        h = h.reshape( -1, x.shape[2], self.num_classes )
        
        # Softmax for inference, log-softmax for trainning
        if self.softmax_enabled:
            h = F.softmax( h, dim=-1 )
        else:
            h = F.log_softmax( h, dim=-1 )
        
        return h
```
I export the model to ONNX using the following lines

```
dummy_inputs, _, dummy_lengths = generate_padded_minibatch_for_pytorch( sampler, device )
 torch.onnx.export( self, (dummy_inputs, dummy_lengths), pathModel, verbose=False, input_names = [ "padded_sequences", "lengths" ], output_names = [ "output" ])
```

And this is the exported ONNX file

[batch_of_sequences_issue.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/3370308/batch_of_sequences_issue.zip)

Can you please take a look at it? It worked great with the ORT code from a few weeks ago (unfortunately I do not remember the commit as I unwittingly deleted the branch). 

**Urgency**
I am stuck with this.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows 10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: Compiled from source 
- Commit ID: 2714576d0ae89f553874394d12c1f3cb4724a6de
- Python version: 3.6
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2017
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version: Issue also occurs with CPU
- GPU model and memory:

**To Reproduce**
Describe steps/code to reproduce the behavior: Supply a batch of variable length sequences to the model.

**Expected behavior**
I expect ORT to be able to extract the correct tensor shapes from the input and run successfully as it did when using the code pulled a few weeks ago.

**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

**Additional context**
[batch_of_sequences_issue.zip](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/files/3370308/batch_of_sequences_issue.zip)

body:
Root cause addressed, will send a PR.
@xgirones By they way, Is it possible for us to put your model in our build pipeline to make sure no regression in future?

This is great news, thanks!

Yes, of course. You can use it freely if you find it convenient. It is just a toy model I created to learn more about the best loss functions for sequences.

issue.title: CUDNN_RNN_DATA_LAYOUT_SEQ_MAJOR_UNPACKED works with CUDNN_RNN_PADDED_…

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
Fix issue: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/1400
Set CUDNN_RNN_DATA_LAYOUT_SEQ_MAJOR_UNPACKED and CUDNN_RNN_PADDED_IO_ENABLED mode, so that it will auto fill 0 for the shorter sequences and get correct result.

body:
The fix is merged. Also sorted sequence_lengths is not a limitation any more. Your first model also works. I'll add them to our test pipeline.
Great thanks for your findings!
@xgirones Do you mind to close the issue or you still need some verification?
Closing it... Thanks for your help!

issue.title: "CUDA driver version is insufficent for CUDA runtime version" exception raised when calling OrtCreateSessionFromArray in spite of the CUDA provider not being selected in session options

labels.name: contributions welcome
labels.description: lower priority issues for the core ORT teams

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
It should be possible to use the ONNX runtime shared library compiled with CUDA support on systems lacking a compatible GPU, provided that the CUDA provider is not selected in session options. It seems that this was the default behavior time ago. However, when calling the _OrtCreateSessionFromArray_ function on an instance of the shared library compiled from code pulled from the master branch in 13/7/2019 the following exception is raised:

   onnxruntime::CudaCall CUDA failure 35: CUDA driver version is insufficient for CUDA runtime version.

The call stack is

```
onnxruntime.dll!onnxruntime::CudaCall<enum cudaError,1>(cudaError retCode, const char * exprString, const char * libName, cudaError successCode, const char * msg) Line 91 at e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\providers\cuda\cuda_call.cc(91)
onnxruntime.dll!onnxruntime::GPUDataTransfer::GPUDataTransfer() Line 12	at e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\providers\cuda\gpu_data_transfer.cc(12)
[Inline Frame] onnxruntime.dll!std::make_unique() Line 2539 at c:\program files (x86)\microsoft visual studio\2017\enterprise\vc\tools\msvc\14.16.27023\include\memory(2539)
onnxruntime.dll!onnxruntime::InferenceSession::InferenceSession(const onnxruntime::SessionOptions & session_options, onnxruntime::logging::LoggingManager * logging_manager) Line 109 at e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\session\inference_session.cc(109)
[Inline Frame] onnxruntime.dll!std::make_unique(const onnxruntime::SessionOptions &&) Line 2539	at c:\program files (x86)\microsoft visual studio\2017\enterprise\vc\tools\msvc\14.16.27023\include\memory(2539)
onnxruntime.dll!`anonymous namespace'::CreateSessionImpl<<lambda_4767107063818b362d43c342e703dc4b> >(OrtEnv * env, const OrtSessionOptions * options, OrtCreateSessionFromArray::__l3::<lambda_4767107063818b362d43c342e703dc4b> loader, OrtSession * * out) Line 370 at e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\session\onnxruntime_c_api.cc(370)
onnxruntime.dll!OrtCreateSessionFromArray(OrtEnv * env, const void * model_data, unsigned __int64 model_data_length, const OrtSessionOptions * options, OrtSession * * out) Line 414 at e:\repo\ort\onnxruntime\core\session\onnxruntime_c_api.cc(414)
```

At first glance it appears that the cause could be the following code in inference_session.cc (line 109)

```
  // Register data transfer methods.
#ifdef USE_CUDA
  data_transfer_mgr_.RegisterDataTransfer(std::make_unique<GPUDataTransfer>());
#endif
```
Mi impression is that the `data_transfer_mgr_.RegisterDataTransfer(std::make_unique<GPUDataTransfer>());` statement in the _InferenceSession_ constructor is executed irrespectively of the CUDA provider being selected in the session options or not.

Moreover, it seems that the shared library has now  a direct dependency on **cublas64_10.dll**, whereas in previous versions of the library this was a delay-load dependency. This dll should be configured as delay-load like the other CUDA dependencies in order to enable the deployment of the onnxruntime shared library without having to redistribute the CUDA binaries on CPU only systems.

**Urgency**
I am stuck on this.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Source
- ONNX Runtime version: Code pulled from the master branch in 13/7/2019
- Python version: 3.6
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): 2017
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source):
- CUDA/cuDNN version: 10.1/7.6
- GPU model and memory:

**To Reproduce**
Call the  _OrtCreateSessionFromArray_ function on the onnxruntime shared library compiled with CUDA support on a system without a compatible GPU.

**Expected behavior**
1- It should be possible to use the ONNX Runtime shared library compiled with CUDA support on systems lacking a compatible GPU, provided that the CUDA provider is not selected in session options. 
2- All CUDA dependencies should be configured as delay-load.

**Screenshots**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

**Additional context**
Add any other context about the problem here. If the issue is about a particular model, please share the model details as well to facilitate debugging.
